safe: stock assessments in Rmarkdown

Ben Williams

2023-08-23

Goal

The goal of safe is to create a formally structured set of .Rmd files to produce a SAFE report that is reproducible. Since we often collaborate with folks who are not R/Rmarkdown/Quarto savvy, and we need 508 compliance this package outputs a word .docx file.

Background

There is a lot of information out there about using markdown, R markdown, bookdown, pandoc, LaTeX, and YAML. We aren’t going to cover all of that, we are going to target generating pdf documents (maybe word and webpages if desired) using Rmarkdown/bookdown in the RStudio IDE.
Important “By tailoring your work to a single output format, you may improve the appearance and performance of a single output format, but at the expense of this transferability.” - Xie et al.2022
That means making a .Rmd file that produces exactly what you want in .pdf typically will not be correctly displayed in .docx or .html.

If you want other/additional options then look at rmarkdown and RStudio markdown intro and bookdown are all quite informative. Be sure to have this all up and running, and update your packages

R 4.1.2+
RStudio v21.09.2+
install.packages("bookdown")
A version of LaTeX if you want tp produce any .pdf docs (recommend tinytex)

install.packages('tinytex')
tinytex::install_tinytex()
tinytex::pdflatex('test.tex')

Things you may have heard…

But may not know what they are

Programs/packages

  • markdown a (very) simple markup language used for formatting text, gets converted to a specified output by pandoc.
  • Rmarkdown a flavor of markdown (there are many)
  • Sweave R function that allows for combining R code with LaTeX, pretty much usurped by Rmarkdown these days
  • LaTeX (pronounced lah-tech) typesetting software, very powerful, steep learning curve. Necessary to create .pdf documents
  • knitr “Sweave reborn” - K. Broman“
  • bookdown R package for formatting multi-chapter documents in Rmd
  • blogdown R package for making websites using Rmd
  • pagedown R package for making paginated html documents - basically html that looks kinda .pdf like
  • pkgdown R package for creating Rpackage documentation website
  • quarto Separate program that effectively acts like Rmd, but for multiple languages (R, Python, Julia) - essential where things are going, don’t worry it renders Rmd files.

Other items

  • YAML a heading of sorts

  • chunk or block a section of code that can be compiled with a Rmd document starts and ends with 3 backticks ```

  • bibtex aka “use bibtex for your bibliography”

    • store references in a .bib file
    • bibtex & biber are programs that interface the .bib file with LaTeX
    • natbib & biblatex are LaTeX packages that format references

  • csl citation style language - format your references

  • css cascading style sheet - format html

  • template Rmd pre-formatted templates, contain a skeleton

Install and setup

Workflow

Setup an R project, include sub directories for data, R scripts, figures, documents. Won’t matter so much to start, but is very important further along.

project
  |-- data
  |-- R
  |-- figs
  |-- tables
  |-- presentation

Install the R package as you would for any other github based package.

# install.packages("remotes")
remotes::install_github("BenWilliams-NOAA/safe")

Then open a new R markdown file.

A panel open up, click on From Template and then click either safe or partial_safe. Name the file safe and give it a location that you want to have the document. Then hit OK.

A folder named safe will be placed in the location previously identified. Note: this assumes, and works best, if your assessment is setup as an Rproject.

In our example folder structure above it would look like this:

project
  |-- data
  |-- R
  |-- figs
  |-- tables
  |-- presentation
  |-- safe

In the case of a “full safe” there will be a number of files in the folder.

Layout

It may seem like there is a lot going on, but it will hopefully make sense soon…

  • safe.Rmd - parent document
  • 01 - summary.Rmd - summary section
  • 01a,b,c - tables that may (or not) go in the summary
  • 02 through 14 - various sections as identified in our previous stock assessment guidelines document
  • _bookdown.yml helper for adjusting fig/table captions
  • .lua files additional helper files for author blocks and figure captions
  • safe_bibby.bib - bibliography file
  • skeleton.log LaTeX log file from building the package
  • styles.css a place to adjust appearances if you are outputting to .html
  • template.docx - a template file to use stock assessment guildelines formats

The reason for the independent files is that each child document can be turned on or off when needed and additionally it facilitates group workflow via github. For example, collaborators could communicate who is responsible for each section, once they are pushed up someone else can edit, in this manner merge conflicts can be reduced, if not eliminated.

Editing

First open the safe.Rmd file, then change the params: section in the YAML at the top of the file. Here I’ve change it to how I have the GOA northern rockfish setup.

The YAML will pull everything in correctly (or should anyway!), I recommend entering the species/stock name as lower case so that it can be used later as inline R code.

There is a load chunk that has global variables in it. These variables will be available to all the child documents.

If there are any sections that you do not want to run simply chang the eval = T to eval = F.

To create a document simply hit the knit button in Rstudio. Note: I keep the format in .html for editing and switch to word_document2: when I’m ready to finalize, I also turn off the table and figures sections if I’m just focused on writing/editing text

The “main table” has been pre-formatted and provided in a function safe::main_table().

Example data for different tiers to work with this function are in the safe/data folder.

The “main table” is generated in 01a-main_table.Rmd Note: Tiers 2 &4 are not currently represented, also for Tiers 5&6 just enter 1 for catch data (c1, c2, c3).

References

Viva la bibtex! We are going to need a bibliography file, it will be in a .bib format, and will be placed in the YAML a la bibliography: references.bib

A standard .bib file contains items that looks something like:

@article{CitekeyArticle,
  author   = "P. J. Cohen",
  title    = "The independence of the continuum hypothesis",
  journal  = "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences",
  year     = 1963,
  volume   = "50",
  number   = "6",
  pages    = "1143--1148",
}

My recommendation is to slightly change this so that it will work well with bibtex and biblatex, mainly this is using a single CitekeyArticle style and using {} instead of " throughout. Otherwise there are times when capitalization will not work correctly.

@article{Akira2001,
      Author = {Akira, N and Yanagimoto, T and Mito, K and Katakura, S},
      DOI = {10.1046/j.1365-2419.2001.00181.x},
      ISSN = {10546006},
      Journal = {Fisheries Oceanography},
      Number = {4},
      Pages = {367--375},
      Title = {Interannual variability in growth of walleye pollock, \emph{Theragra chalcogramma}, in the central {Bering Sea}},
      URL = {http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1365-2419.2001.00181.x},
      Volume = {10},
      Year = {2001}
}

@article{Ahrestani2013,
  doi = {10.1038/srep03125},
  url = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/srep03125},
  year = {2013},
  month = {nov},
  publisher = {Nature Publishing Group},
  volume = {3},
  author = {Farshid S. Ahrestani and Mark Hebblewhite and Eric Post},
  title = {The importance of observation versus process error in analyses of global ungulate populations},
  journal = {Scientific Reports}
}

Note that there is LaTeX code in the Akira2001 title \emph or \textit is used to italicize, and braces are used to capitalize {Bering Sea}.

To use this in a document it would look like:

---
title: "test"
author: "Ben Williams"
date: "4/20/2022"
output: 
  bookdown::pdf_document2
bibliography: references.bib
---

Something about limited entry management [@Akira2001] and @Ahrestani2013 talks about process error. 
Also, some opinions were stated [@Akira2001; @Ahrestani2013].

# References

This will produce an output that looks like:

Something about limited entry management (Akira et al. 2001) and Ahrestani et al. (2013) talks about
process error. Also, some opinions were stated (Akira et al. 2001; Ahrestani et al. (2013)).

References

Ahrestani, F.S., Hebblewhite, M., and Post, E. 2013. The importance of observation versus process er-
ror in analyses of global ungulate populations. Scientific Reports 3. Nature Publishing Group. doi:
10.1038/srep03125.
Akira, N., Yanagimoto, T., Mito, K., and Katakura, S. 2001. Interannual variability in growth of walleye
pollock, theragra chalcogramma, in the central Bering Sea. Fisheries Oceanography 10(4): 367–375. doi:
10.1046/j.1365-2419.2001.00181.x.

Note the square brackets around Akira and not around Ahrestani and the differing outputs. Additionally, see that the references are in alphabetical order.

There are numerous entry types for .bib files: article, book, booklet, conference… see here

You can also find styles - no more changing reference formats by hand.
Styles or build/tweak your own These are added to the YAML as well by changing the .csl file.

---
title: "test"
author: "Ben Williams"
date: "4/20/2022"
output: 
  bookdown::pdf_document2
bibliography: references.bib
csl: canjfas.csl
---

Citations keys take the @ sign while square brackets and/or minus signs introduce variation

[@smith2020] becomes (Smith 2020)
@smith2020 becomes Smith (2020)
[-@smith2020] becomes (2020)
-@smith2020 becomes 2020
[@smith2020 35] becomes (Smith 2020, p.35)
[@smith2020 33-35] becomes (Smith 2020, pp. 33-35)
[@smith2020, ch. 1] becomes (Smith 2020, ch. 1)
[@smith2020; Jones2022] becomes (Smith 2020; Jones 2020)
[see @smith2020, for details] becomes (see Smith 2020, for details)
@smith2020 [33-35] becomes (Smith 2020, pp. 33-35)

Odds and ends

R markdown structure

YAML

Rhymes with camel: Header material that tells R markdown how to render your document.
Important indentation and spacing matter!

  • When you knit:

    • .Rmd -> knitr -> .md -> pandoc -> out
    • output can be .docx, .html, .pdf, and others

  • YAML: ‘Yet Another Markup Language’ morphed to ‘YAML Ain’t Markup Language’

(Very) brief primer on LaTeX

A TeX distribution can be thought of like base R, generally useful but doesn’t provide loads of functionality. Much like R, LaTeX requires packages that provide a range of options and functionality. There are many (4,000+). Packages can be added to preamble (YAML) of your document in a couple of ways:

  1. using a separate file
    output:
      # rmdformats::downcute:
      bookdown::pdf_document2:
        includes:
          in_header: "preamble.tex"
  1. adding statements directly to the YAML
    header-includes:
        \usepackage{fvextra}
        \DefineVerbatimEnvironment{Highlighting}{Verbatim}{
          breaksymbolleft={},
          showspaces = false,
          showtabs = false,
          breaklines,
          commandchars=\\\{\}
        }
        \pagenumbering{gobble}
        \linenumbers

or 3. using the extra_dependencies statement

    output:
      bookdown::pdf_document2:
        extra_dependencies:
          caption: ["labelfont={bf}"]
          hyperref: ["unicode=true", "breaklinks=true"]
          lmodern: null

CTAN houses LaTeX packages. A couple of good packages to know about are:

  • multicol & multirow which allow for more columns or rows, handy for complex tables
  • geometry allows for specification of document size and margins
  • hyperref allows for easier inclusion of hyperlinks
  • fvextra automatic line breaks etc.
  • float keeps figs/tables where you want them - you will want this

A fair number of these packages are rolled into bookdown but it doesn’t hurt to know how to look for their options or other packages.

Learn LaTeX in 30 minutes hahaha…

Syntax

R markdown follows the syntax in Pandoc’s markdown - have a look at the cheat sheet
I’ll only cover some of the more esoteric aspects of the syntax.

Lines

Line spacing of text become quite valuable particularly for larger documents.

Sentences on the same line will be read in line and produce the same output.

I have one space following. So continues as a single line in a paragraph.
I have two spaces following.  So continues as a single line in a paragraph.
I have three spaces following.   So continues as a single line in a paragraph.

Results in:
I have one space following. So continues as a single line in a paragraph.
I have two spaces following. So continues as a single line in a paragraph.
I have three spaces following. So continues as a single line in a paragraph.

I have one space following with a return._ 
So continues as a paragraph._
Pretty much how we normally write things._   

I have two spaces following with a return.__  
So continues as a paragraph.__
Which can get a bit odd as each is a new line, but the same paragraph (almost list form).__

I have three spaces following with a return.___  
So continues as a paragraph.___
Produces the same as two spaces.___

Results in:
I have one space following with a return. So continues as a paragraph. Pretty much how we normally write things.

I have two spaces following with a return.
So continues as a paragraph.
Which can get a bit odd as each is a new line, but the same paragraph (almost list form).

I have three spaces following with a return.
So continues as a paragraph.
Produces the same as two spaces.

I have one space following with a return._ 
So continues as a paragraph.  

A space between lines starts a new paragraph...

Results in:
I have one space following with a return. So continues as a single line in a paragraph.

A space between lines starts a new paragraph…

Note: Multiple blank lines between paragraphs reduce to one.

When writing follow each sentence with one space and a new line, because tracking down issues and editing text (finding the correct location or id location on GitHub) is much easier later on if your document looks like:

Pollock have been sampled in the western Gulf of Alaska (Figure \@ref{fig:map}; Table \@ref(tab:sample)) during spring acoustic surveys since 1983 [@NMFS2013]. 
Macroscopic estimates of female maturity have been determined using a 5-stage [@Stahl2008a] or 8-stage key [@Williams2007], which were condensed to immature/mature with pre-spawning and later stages considered mature.
Fish were measured for fork length to the nearest cm and weighed in grams; ages were determined by the AFSC Age and Growth Program [@Matta2012]. 
Ovary samples of mature pollock were collected opportunistically from AFSC trawl surveys and stored in 10\% buffered formalin solution. 
Each sample had associated location and date of capture information as well as individual weight (g), fork length (cm) and age information. 
The spatial extent of these data is dependent upon the sampling location of the NMFS survey trawls and incorporates regional variability. 
Samples were typically collected from winter pre-spawning cruises, allowing us to examine annual variability.

instead of this

Pollock have been sampled in the western Gulf of Alaska (Figure \@ref{fig:map}; Table \@ref(tab:sample)) during spring acoustic surveys since 1983 [@NMFS2013]. Macroscopic estimates of female maturity have been determined using a 5-stage [@Stahl2008a] or 8-stage key [@Williams2007], which were condensed to immature/mature with pre-spawning and later stages considered mature. Fish were measured for fork length to the nearest cm and weighed in grams; ages were determined by the AFSC Age and Growth Program [@Matta2012]. Ovary samples of mature pollock were collected opportunistically from AFSC trawl surveys and stored in 10\% buffered formalin solution. Each sample had associated location and date of capture information as well as individual weight (g), fork length (cm) and age information. The spatial extent of these data is dependent upon the sampling location of the NMFS survey trawls and incorporates regional variability. Samples were typically collected from winter pre-spawning cruises, allowing us to examine annual variability.

Behind the scenes this will look like:

Where every sentence starts on it’s own line, instead of this:

Where the entire paragraph is treated as a single sentence.

Spaces on lines that start with a vertical line | are kept

| one-space
|     five-space
|        eight-space

Text with the syntax <!--your comments --> is omitted from output

[visit my website](https://www.noaa.gov/) becomes visit my website
[www.noaa.gov](https://www.noaa.gov/) becomes www.noaa.gov
or just wright the website https://www.noaa.gov/ - which will be converted when the doc is compiled.

Nested lists

Can be generated using *, +, or - or can be numbered.

1. play
   - ski
   - camp  
2. sleep
3. work
   - computer
      + programs
  1. play
    • ski
    • camp
  2. sleep
  3. work
    • computer
      • programs

The maths

Inline equations go between a pair of single dollar signs $ — with no space between the signs and the equation itself

Einstein figured out \(E=mc^2\), but you are smarter. $E=mc^2$

Block equations go in between a pair of double dollar signs.
Einstein figured out \[E=mc^2,\] but you are smarter. $$E=mc^2,$$

Numbered equations are easy (in .pdf), just need to bring in some LaTeX.

Einstein figured out \[\begin{equation} E=mc^2, \end{equation}\] but you are smarter.

\begin{equation}
E=mc^2,
\end{equation}

Recommendations

  1. keep figures and tables separate
  2. use flextable to generate tables
    • bring tables in as .csv files then manipulate (or edit in Excel and append to Word doc if the table is too complicated)
